- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text: i was taken advantage of as a teen at anime los angeles 2013. Â nikki jermaczonak, also known as piggynukka, a woman i trusted, compelled me to binge drink when i was a teenager. i accepted these drinks because i did not want to upset her or ~kill the mood~. after hanging out for a while, i went back up to my room because i felt i had a little too much. about 15 to 20 minutes later, i recieved a call from nikki pressuring me to come hang out more at the pool deck, to which i reluctantly accepted. after shoving a plastic kids beach bucket filled with jungle juice in my face, she wanted to walk around the con. we laughed and had a good time playing pachinko and ddr for a bit. at this point in time we were both completely hammered and not in control of our actions, stumbling around like two idiots. nikki brings up the idea to go to her room because she wants me to meet some of her friends as well as play some gamecube. i donâ€™t protest because i had lost the ability to protest due to being inebriated. we hung out for a good half hour continuing to drink. her friends left. next thing i know iâ€™m letting her put temporary shrek tattoos on my face, dry heaving Â over the toilet and dancing around to wildcat by ratatat, Â thatâ€™s when it finally happened.she lightly tackled me onto the bed and shifted us into a cuddling position. confessing her true feelings to me. i said nothing because i was just shaking due to shock. this was the first time a woman had touched me in this manner. she then pulled my face in close for a deep kiss, she then laid my head back down on her shoulder. i could barely speak without slurring and could barely move. this is when her friend came in and started accusing me of the worst. i stumbled my way out of there falling over and hitting my head in the hallway. i went back to my room and cried in the bathroom. for years i told myself i liked it due to the sheer amount of endorphins running through my body, but that doesn't mean i consented. #piggynukka #sexualassault #cosplay #metoo

text: i'm celebrating my one year surgiversary y'all.  i am so happy and so proud!! i'm definitely not going back ever! i have several giveaways coming on my instagram @lezettechristinemua to celebrate.  i have had a few companies who donated to my success and i've also purchased some of my favorite products as well. i never thought i would be where i am today, alive and 140 pounds down. i had vsg 12/11/17 i was 348 pounds and dying because of my blood disease.  last year i was hospitalized every other week to receive a life saving infusion and now this year i only need to go in once every 2 months. its been nothing shy of incredible!! today i stepped on the scale and weighed in at 208. i also celebrated a nsv i was able to fit in a victoria secrets large top and a size 14 vigoss jeans not plus sized!! holy cow i'm on top of the world. i want to shout it from the rooftop seriously i'm so happy right now!! i am extremely strict, and dedicated i make sure to get in my protein,  water and vitamins. i walk a mile a few times a week and continue to fight. i would love to help you on your journey whether you are preop, post op or have fallen of the wagon. i'm here to tell you it's not too late every day is a new day and if you just have a little faith you can move mountains i post recipes,  motivation,  ideas and photos to help you all #bethebestversionofyou #againstallodds #aginginreverse #nevertoolate #youareenough #youcandoit #onestepatatime #bethechange #methemoglobinemia #metoo #knowyourworth #itstartswithone @lezettechristinemua

text:
we talk about empowering girls, we share impacting and inspiring videos, articles on various topics related to gender equality, violence, etc. we all voiced out for #metoo. when you do all this, what stops you from taking the next step - action. our empower workshop is conceptualized to equip the young girls & women of all ages basic self-defense techniques, equipping them to fight back both mentally & physically during untoward situations. 
knowing how to identify a suspicious situation and protecting yourself from it could be a life-saving tool in event of an attack, that's why we at aware encourage women to dedicate a few hours to learn basic self-defense. we teach women and girls how to be better aware of their surroundings and go over basic moves that could help save their lives.

join us to learn how you can defend yourself in similar situations. 
share the stage with like-minded women and find your super power. 
#nomorenirbhaya- an aware initiative

date: 16th december, sunday
time: 10 am to 1 pm
exact venue will be shared with the registered participants

registration is free, but mandatory. register @ bit.ly/emp16dec or via whatsapp "nomorenirbhaya" to 8122241688

let's build a better society where every girl and woman feel safe, empowered and respected!

text:
i'm a survivor!!! it's a big thanksgiving day for me because it's exactly 6years today 09:12:2018 that i would have been killed for nothing if not for god's grace. 
thanks to god for major healing this year. 
i'll like to address some of the pains that leads many to depression after being assaulted.

there's a lot more injuries inflicted on the victims of violence survivors mentally than physical as some of those who are supposed to enforce law also tries to take advantage to reap them off financially and even  ready to abuse sexually at every slight opportunity. thank god for the few people l've met as well who stands for nothing but truth and justice. 
the trauma is sometimes unexplainable and it's such a pity that we are in a society where the victims are condemned when trying to speak out there by most withdraw to their shell feeling worthless then isolate themselves and then depression sets in to open the door to suicide thoughts. 
a problem shared they say is half solved, if you are a victim of violence survivor or you are still being abused presently, speak out whenever you feel like talking about it, it's a process that helps you heal. 
don't let anyone who knows nothing about your struggle shut you up when you are trying to speak your mind. love yourself enough to do what will help you live again by not keeping all the hurt inside cause it could be deadly. 
i'm thankful to god because the attack that would have killed me,my brother and a neighbor made me stronger, i find it unbelievable when people share with me and say your songs lifted me and gave me hope again.that is priceless and i get fulfilled each time i have the opportunity to get someone motivated. 
i want to do more, so to help me do more get my new song titled get up produced by da unit to be released on 18:12:18 and stay motivated. god bless you all. #speakout #pray #believesurvivors #believewoman #notoviolenceagainstwomen #abuse #domesticviolence #notoinjustice #metoo #suicideisnotthewayout, #noviolence #keepyourselfmotivated #getuponyourfeetandstandtallagain #getuponyourfeetnow #advocacy #nobullying #equity #everyonedeservestobeheard #nobullies #strong

text:
tw: rape, language, ipv
â€œwhen i was seventeen i fell head over heels in what i believed was love with a guy who was 21. we ended up married within the first year of dating and although he was sweet i noticed that a lot of things changed. we went from holding hands and cuddling during the day to him never making eye contact with me. he stopped working, and i ended up working two jobs. we moved six times in the same year and barely had money to afford food- living in a one bedroom apartment getting to work with a car that was gifted to us and owning one chair and a tv off craigslist. if we were watching a movie at home, he got the chair and i sat on the floor. he wouldn't let me lay next to him in our bed, and only ever touched me if he wanted sex. we didnt hold hands unless he was trying to seduce me, he wouldnt even sit next to me unless it meant he could pin me down on my back and face fuck me that night. he stopped telling me he loved me nine months into the marriage, (but i said it every day, and yet i still stayed a year and a half in...). the end of the marriage was messy. he texted me asking for a divorce and never came home that day. a week later i came "home" and he was packing my stuff. i asked him to stay, i told him we could work things out, i stood in the doorway with a 15 page letter asking for another chance. i told him i'd let him use me more, i'd be prettier, i'd work harder for us, i'd do whatever he asked me to do if he would just stay. he grabbed me by the shoulders and threw me across the hall into our bathroom. i ended up with a black eye and bruised ribs. when we had to meet up to sign the divorce paperwork he said all he had left to do was hate fuck me and he'd be happy with how things ended... i threw up in my car on the way home i was so sick from that one sentence. it was about three years of hell, looking back i'm glad he wanted to leave, for whatever his reasons were. i'm glad i made it out.â€ -anonymous

text:
recovering from abuse is hard work.

you may feel worthless, tired and ready to quit. but there is hope and you are not a lost cause. for a long time i felt like damaged goods, and i doubted i would feel whole again. but with the help of family, friends, counseling, taking risks, and especially my relationship with god, i've made leaps and bounds in my recovery. 
it's possible to feel better, be better and do better. you are not too damaged to have a happy life, to be used to help others and to positively be used by god.

have faith.

text:
just a note to my baby girl when she was only 6 months old: as you know baby girl...before you were ever born, it was me who carried you for 9 long months. 
the day you came into this world, the moment we met, it was all about you and me, too. it was my bare chest that you needed to rest upon and latch to...it was my heart beating that helped regulate yours and my everyday choices that helped to form you into the little human you were and are.
your first few weeks, you were held by many others and even fed by many...but it was my milk that kept you growing. you slept on my chest your first few weeks because i was so scared to lose you or that i wouldn't hear if something happened. i felt every breath and your heartbeat every night.
i know it isn't always going to be about just you and me. of course, you will still need me. but...every passing day it becomes more and more clear that you are gaining more and more independence. you are only 6 months old but i know you won't be a baby much longer. i wish i could just slow time down. 
pretty soon i know you won't need me to carry you. you will learn to crawl, then walk, then run or you may just skip crawling and run at this rate. when i try to cuddle you, you will be eager to explore the world. 
soon you won't need me to change your diapers or dress you..you will want to pick out your own clothes - which i'm sure will be quite interesting. you won't need me to feed you. you won't need me to read to you. 
i am realizing more and more that there is only a little bit of time left when it's still really just you and me. in no time, your life will be filled with family, friends, classmates, teachers, and many others. 
for now i'm going to be right here, holding you tight. just you and me...because i know just how quickly time is going already. i love you sweet girl!

text:
i just wanted to take the time to thank every single person who has reached out with words of encouragement and support. one of the hardest parts of this journey has been the feeling of isolation. when you reach out to someone who is experiencing or recovering from domestic abuse, you are making an impact you couldn't imagine. 
i had a small but mighty army of friends who never left my side throughout the cycle of violence and abuse. even when i pushed them away, disappointed them, isolated from them, they never stopped believing in me. they picked up the phone, they showed up, they took me in, they came to the hospital with me, they encouraged me to report and protect myself. i will spend eternity thanking god for them. 
speaking out on social media has been extremely difficult. there are feelings of shame associated with being assaulted by your partner. the person who is supposed to love you. but you guys have helped turn shame into empowerment. i've gone from victim to survivor. from weak to warrior. so thank you, every single one of you! you've touched my heart, and impacted my life. we.are.stronger.together.

text: this young lady changed my life ğŸ™‚and my way of thinking (which is very rare for me because i consider myself open minded) i am her tutor / mentor . she was very upset during our session about a group discussion on sexual assault at her school. she said there are no african-american women in the discussion. i didn't think it was that big a deal. i figured "a victim is a victim rite? what does race have to do with it?" but i could tell from her response to me that i was wrong. so i decided to volunteer and be that voice for her. i figured "ok , i'll speak to your class. i'm a teacher. why not?" it turned out to be a huge youth consent summit  on sexual assault . the "consent is _____" summit in dc for all dc college preparatory schools ! i ended up speaking in front of 500 + people ! (i couldn't back down on my promise once i told her) i never realized my story was so important. i definitely never imagined it could positively inspire and relate to so many. and i realized it is important for african-american woman to be part of the shifting conversation and view on rape/ sexual assault. look toward victim healing and not victim blaming, self-hate or shame. i do wake up every morning now happy and with the same pep in my step i had as a kid. my sexual assault in college doesn't haunt me anymore. and i'm sure as hell not scared of that guy anymore, or of not being "cool" or what anyone has to say about me. it was not easy and a long road , but i am a survivor. and i'm proud to help other victims find their way back to happiness and themselves . i went from her tutor to panelist speaker  and guest of honor in 48 hours! (they gave me an award) #metoo #pave #love #loveyourself #speakout #courage

text: last year i had hoped this blog of sorts would be a place to document my healing journey. instead it seemed to document my relationship journeys. i purposely joined an online group in 2018, and opened myself up, with the help of my counselor. i learned how to start conversations. i learned how to make friends. i learned how to keep some friends. i learned how to recover from the loss of people i thought were friends. i learned how to laugh and i learned how to cry!! i have experienced the full range of emotions this past year. i have learned many lessons. while i complain about not really touching on my past with my counselor, i have spent the year learning how to live and how to love again. thank you, 2018!!

text:
when the #metoo movement began i received messages from women and men telling me that i was arguing a lost cause. i was being irrational and it was just millennials looking to be upset about one more thing. 
within my core i knew it wasnâ€™t one more thing.
it was a battle cry rising.
thirty years ago today i was raped. december 11. at fourteen years old. each year,when this day rolls around, i find my body aching for relief. to be heard.and each year i think ,this year, this is the year i will feel something. a fourteen year old child went numb that michigan winter.
everyday i choose to fight for that 14 year old girl. to walk towards healing. 
when we went to trial that spring thirty years ago i left the courtroom watching my rapist walk free. â€œnot guiltyâ€ still pounds in my chest.
sometimes justice looks like healing. 
i beg of you,all around are women and men aching for justice. aching to feel something besides the shame that has suffocated them for years. so when we say #metoo believe us.  we are trying to breathe again. to have our story matter.this is our battle cry. and we will rise.

#yearofhealing #yearofforgiveness #goldfinches #yearofhope #hopewriters #justice #metoo #womensmarch

how am i supposed to heal when 
i still feel their hands on my body 
i can still hear what they whispered while they took me
on most days i revisit that moment 
in that moment i shake 
my heart pounds like drums
my body becomes weak 
my mind throws thousands of thoughts at me
i pray that 
that feeling goes away
feeling the dirt they left on my chest
feeling the guilt telling myself it was my fault 
iâ€™m at a war with myself
or iâ€™m at war with my past self 
at night i can still hear the lies that were told 
the lies i told to keep them safe
i still remember the first time they took me
it was the first time i ever felt that invisible tape over my mouth
ever since then i have tried multiple times to remove it 
but it wonâ€™t come off
my healing isnâ€™t here 
right now itâ€™s nonexistent 
itâ€™s a dream for now
itâ€™s a dream that sooner than later 
i will never achieve ***
-deniseâ›ˆ

text:
â€¢ coping skill of the day: color breathing â€¢ what is color breathing? color breathing is a coping skill that combines imagery with intentional breathing to help modulate intense feelings, stabilize panic, soothe pain, or to even feel more grounded. it's an invaluable tool  for everyone - but is especially beneficial to those who struggle with anxiety, flashbacks, dissociation and more.
.
there are many ways to perform color breathing; customization is key. one of the most common ways is to imagine a very calming color (perhaps blues or purples, or yellows and golds for some) being inhaled deep into your lungs and immediately finding all of the unrest, anxiety or pain inside of you, enveloping it, healing it. then, assign a color to all the upsetting or painful emotions (perhaps reds or oranges or blacks) and watch as that color leaves you with a long exhale. repeat this deep inhaling and exhaling of colors until you feel more at ease. you may even find that the colors change a bit as you start to improve. this version is most commonly used for anxiety, anger, or physical pain. but, some find it helpful for emotions like sadness and grief, embarrassment or shame. ..preferring to inhale invigorating and light colors and exhale the heavy weighted colors of sadness, loneliness or guilt.
.
another method is to concentrate more on the exhale, watching as the colors go from bright fiery shades to cooler tones, like a gradient. or vice versa if you need lightness, warmth or energy. this is particularly useful if you haven't been able to identify *which* feelings you're experiencing or have no idea "what you need" to inhale - you just know it's intense. so, exhaling reds and oranges until you get down to the calmer end of the 'rainbow' can be really effective in dialing things down (or up, if reversed!)
.
there are many ways to customize this tool to work best for you. the more you can truly visualize it and believe in its effectiveness, the more success you'll have! there are also so many other ways to apply this template. how would you go about color breathing?Â ideas and suggestions from other survivors can often be what makes things click for someone else!
.

text:
(swipe) bill cosby's lawyers on tuesday filed a list of nearly a dozen alleged trial errors as they appeal his sexual assault conviction and three- to 10-year prison term.

the defense asked to have the 81-year-old disgraced comedian released from a suburban #philadelphia prison while his appeal proceeds, but their pleas have so far been rejected.

the lawyers said trial judge steven o'neill had an alleged feud with a pretrial witness, the ex-prosecutor who had declined to charge cosby a decade earlier. and they said his decisions to preside over the case, let five other accusers testify, air cosby's prior deposition testimony about quaaludes and dismiss the ex-prosecutor's promise not to charge him are mistakes that warrant a new trial. "the trial court erred in failing to disclose his bias against district attorney (bruce) castor, and in failing to recuse himself, prior to determining (his) credibility," wrote lawyer brian perry, the latest of more than a dozen lawyers to represent cosby in the case.

a jury convicted cosby at a spring retrial of drugging and molesting a temple university employee in 2004, in what became the first celebrity trial of the #metoo era.

cosby â€” whose estimated fortune from his popular tv shows, comedy tours and product pitches once topped $400 million â€” was convicted of drugging and sexually assaulting accuser #andreaconstand. the entertainer, who is legally blind, spends his days in a one-man cell and private day room in a new state prison about 20 miles from his sprawling estate near #philadelphia, where the crime occurred.

in a deposition in constand's 2005 civil suit, cosby called the 2004 encounter consensual and his feelings for her romantic. constand considered him a mentor with close ties to her boss at #temple, where she worked for the women's basketball team. she was about 30 and cosby, a temple trustee, about 66 at the time. the key issues raised on appeal tuesday include: see below via hollywoodreporter  #billcosby #freebillcosby #farfromfinished

text:
dear @robingwright: if i send this your way, will you autograph it and send it back? have your people get in touch with my people. please and thank you.
.
.
as some of you may recall, i shared a story about how i saw an infomercial on halloween day during the price is right.
.
.
that infomercial was for the president claire hale underwood commemorative plate. .
.
what was remarkable about the infomercial was the fact that it never mentioned it was a gag, nor that it was a promotional tool for the @netflix original series, @houseofcards. it was very funny, but very subtle. you had to be in on the joke.
.
.
i wound up calling the number in the infomercial a few of times. i was able to get through and leave a message with my name and callback number. about a week later, i received a call from mike with a & d fine classics (makers of this plate). i was told i had been awarded a plate. he took my name and address and informed me that the plate would be to me in 4 to 6 weeks.
.
.
guess what arrived today? .
.
i want to give my heartfelt thanks to netflix for this cherished piece of memorabilia. i am very appreciative. merry christmas to me!
.
.

text:
se que estas cansada, pero segui adelante. 
recien escuche el testimonio de violacion que vivio la actriz thelma fardin a manos de juan darthes.

from @yasir.qadhi -  in light of all of the scandals of the #metoo movement, top level male execs in wall street are now following some basic protocols, such as: - never being alone with a female in a closed room

text:
#ruok ?Â¿?Â¿?Â¿?Â¿? saddness is a terrible reality.. its a heaviness you carry deep within your heart that almosts suffocates you..this is where crying comes in handy..it releases the pressure of those clenched emotions you have carried for how ever long you have..for me its a daily struggle im on a journey learning these emotions of life and how they do effect me so i can try and make them better.. please to my friends and family i would appreciate your understanding that mental illness comes in many shapes and forms..many people including myself do have daily struggles and it is while we have supportive people who dont make judgement of us that we thrive the most...everyday all we wish....is to feel normal what ever that may be.. i know many suffer in silence and some like myself we scream and shout lol but please dont be affraid to ask those few words even to a stranger u may see in distress.. r u ok???? it may make all the difference xoxox today im mostly ok.. i hope you are too. xoxox thanks for listening ğŸ˜˜ never feel alone as there is always someone who understands because they struggle too...life is hard and for those who struggle with mental illness it is even harder.. #ruok

text:
very interesting letter from @ucobronchos president today. i hope these new policies are enacted and actually enforced.

these policies definitely were not enforced when i filed multiple harassment claims and my harasser was allowed to keep his job even after admitting to harassing me and threatening to assault me on multiple occasions. that same man was able to continue harassing me for over a year until, after suffering from weekly, sometimes daily panic attacks, i had to leave my job. 
yup. you read that correctly.

for the sake of all women (and men) still on the @ucobronchos campus and those that will be there in the future, i truly hope title ix is taken seriously in the future. 
#metoo

text:
#worldhumanrightsday
#worldhumanrights 
so yesterday was world human rights day.  i'm a day late to the party.  better late than never especially when it's for an issue close to my heart.

the theme for 2018 is #standupforhumanrights

here's to standing up to all forms of xenophobia, standing up against poverty, and standing up for political, civil, economic, social and cultural rights âœŠğŸ½ i'm not a huge fan of social media but one thing it has been is drawn attention to the ills in our world.  this year the focus has rightly been on gender equality with #metoo ,  a spotlight on police killings of black communities and in particular young black men in the us by @kaepernick7 @childishgambino to name but a few and the right for trans equality by our very own @munroebergdorf

god told us the greatest commandment is love and we should "love our neighbours like we love ourselves". this certainly would be one step towards healing the world and making it a better place.  love surely can make the world go round ğŸ’ ğŸŒ

text:
jacob walter anderson, now 23, was given a $400 fine, a recommended three yearsâ€™ probation and ongoing psychological, alcohol and substance abuse counseling. the victim, identified as #donnadoe in court records, said the ex-phi delta theta fraternity president anderson drugged and repeatedly raped her at a #fraternity party when she was a 19-year-old sophomore. #anderson was originally indicted on four counts of sexual assault, and faced two to 20 years in prison and a $10,000 fine. in october, anderson was offered a controversial plea deal for a lesser charge of unlawful restraint. the woman said she felt disoriented after accepting a drink she thought contained punch at a 2016 fraternity house party at #bayloruniversity. she said anderson led her behind a tent and repeatedly raped her while she was gagged and choked.

a warrant said the woman was assaulted until she lost consciousness and anderson left her alone. the warrant said she had vomited on herself and could have choked to death in the backyard. 
the judgeâ€™s decision monday is not the first time that judge ralph #strother has allowed such lenient punishment for #sexcrimes. last year, he sentenced a man to deferred probation after he pleaded guilty in the 2013 rape of a former #baylor student. the judge ordered the man to pay for the womanâ€™s counseling. the man told police the woman had been drunk, according to an affidavit. >>this judge should be kicked off the bench. youâ€™d think it was #kavanaugh rendering judgement in this case â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”-#rapeculture #rapecultureisreal #grossmiscarriageofjustice  #metoo #timesup #sexualassault #rape

text:
i want to share this is a very sad story but important story. the push to expose this awful behavior by buddhist project sunshine is applauded and appreciated.

here is the link (sorry i do not have live links in my feed as this is very long. there are lots of articles if you use the search criteria buddhist project sunshine.

https://thinkprogress.org/colorado-police-investigating-alleged-sexual-assaults-by-buddhist-leaders-d5374c4f702d/?fbclid=iwar3ecwndeulk2fwfjzslupdzkqmv0xm5knvcdnpixf6rtfbnbly1mixpt4g

i have seen this happen in many communities now.Â bikram, anuasara, rigpa, diamond mountainâ€¦

jetsunma tenzin palmo taught me to separate the teachings from the teacher and showed me that, consistent in all buddhist teachings, are valuable guidelines for finding authentic teachers. (easy to find but let me know if you want a list)

i canâ€™t say that i am not dissolutioned by the hierarchical, patriarchal, feudal systems of tibetan buddhism and that i donâ€™t struggle with the desire to â€˜throw the baby out with the bath waterâ€™. i can say that my 25+ year meditation practice has been the strongest foundation and support of my life and humbly state that it has provided me with as discerning wisdom i strive to unfold daily.

i am so interested in how others work with this fucked-up-ness. 
any comments are appreciated.

text:
sex after abuse: part 2/3 â¤ï¸ what to do about the panic?
.
2 things are critical here: your relationship with yourself and your relationship with the other. both are equally important. there are certainly ways you can help yourself, but ultimately this will be resolved with an intimate partner (even if they don't realise this).
.
for all aspects of healing and living again, including sex, i have found from both my personal experience and my research that the key is the body. trauma is registered in the body, changing its neurobiology and physiology, and disconnecting it from the self, living its own reality. so, of course, as sex is such an intimate bodily experience, it can be extremely frightening and triggering - and even more so when the #trauma comes from #sexualabuse. naturally, many can experience extreme panic, or worse (reliving or re-traumatisation, for ex.).
.
luckily, sex can also be healing! not simply the act, but the intimate connection with your own body and the intimate connection with another person. it is intra- and inter-relational connection in a context of safety that enables the healing of trauma and the growth post-trauma. of course, this doesn't happen just through sex, sex isn't an option for everyone and it doesn't have to be, and most importantly it never means you should push yourself to have sex. but if the conditions and timing are right, sex can be one part of the building of your relationship with yourself and with others.
.
there are a few persons who have been key in my healing, for different reasons (and some also who have hindered it). there is one person who was incredibly important without knowing it. at the time, i was confused, scared, and disgusted. but one day, i met someone for whom i felt immense attraction. a natural, beautiful, instantaneous attraction. by being drawn to him, i was drawn out of my trauma - not fully, but enough to embody something that was entirely out of trauma's realm. something strong and real. i won't share the whole story, but overall he was a big part of my reconnection with myself, with my body, with my sensations, and with my emotions. ğŸ¦‹
.
.

i then became aware that i, too, exhibited sexist biases and supported benevolent sexism. this latter kind, as the title implies, isnâ€™t overt, hostile discrimination; but it is insidious, and its existence is correlated with the repression of womenâ€™s rights. â€¢

text:
whilst today marks the 10th of december, otherwise known a
#internationalhumanrightsday it also marks the end of #16daysofactivism.

it is difficult to fully celebrate #humanrightsday because womens rights have not yet been fully recognized, yet womens rights are in fact human rights.

whilst we have flooded your screens and whilst we have been flooded with stats and facts about gender based violence, domestic violence, intimate partner violence, rape, femicide, female genital mutilation, the psychological, social and economic abuse of women and girls, and so much more we must remember that we have barely even scratched the surface.

the number of unreported cases still remains unknown in all these forms of violence metted out against women, womxn and girls. whilst we hope that this countdown has been informative & will help equip you with more tools to fight these societal illls we know we have not covered nearly enough. more stats and facts can be seen from @legalaidsa1 as well as further understanding the process for getting protection orders is also covered in the domestic violence act in south africa.

information on possible shelters that might be able to assist you can be found on http://www.gauteng.gov.za/services/women/pages/shelters.aspx whilst these aren't the only shelters they are a start.

the countdown might have ended but the struggle continues. let's continue to #orangetheworld

with you in revolutionary spirit -  blackwomxncaucus

text: on a monday night in midtown #manhattan, a group of approximately 20 men were baring their #souls. â€œiâ€™m angry that my health is deteriorating. iâ€™m not ready to be an old man,â€ said jeff nichols whoâ€™s 70. ranging in age from 30 to 70, the men were gathered as part of the @themankindproject (mkp), a 33-year-old nonprofit with 24 chapters in the u.s. and 11 regions abroad. it focuses on things like menâ€™s emotional well-being, drawing on elements like carl jungâ€™s theories of the psyche, nonviolent communication, breath work and native american customs. men, who are less likely than women to seek out individual therapy, are increasingly looking for outlets in this fraught cultural moment of political acrimony, widespread economic instability and major societal reckoning over their behavior. at mkp, membership is at an all-time high and enrollment is up 8% over the last year, said boysen hodgson, the director of marketing and communications. â€œwith timeâ€™s up now and #metoo, many men know they have to be more accountable,â€ boysen said. â€œa lot of them are saying, â€˜i donâ€™t want that to be me. i donâ€™t want that to be how #men are seen in the world.â€™â€ @caseykelbaugh took this photo during an mkp weekly meeting in manhattan. visit the link in our profile to read more.

â€” a former baylor university student indicted on four counts of sexual assault won't spend a single day in prison, according to local reports.
instead, a plea agreement allowed jacob walter anderson, an ex-fraternity president, to plead no contest to a lesser charge of unlawful restraint, cnn affiliate kwtx reported.
if the 24-year-old successfully completes three years of deferred probation and pays a $400 fine, his criminal record will be wiped clean of the charge, and he won't have to register as a sex offender, cnn affiliate kwkt said.
the plea agreement between anderson's defense team and the mclennan county, texas, district attorney's office infuriated the victim and her attorney. meanwhile former sex-slave; 16 year old #cyntoiabrown was sentenced by the tennessee supreme court to 50+ years for killing her abuser in an attempt to save her own life. in a constitutional; democratic society how does regional #jurisprudence play a role as its very strange how justices and judges from the southern; more conservative states reason on cases verses those of the north with a more liberal mindset. it often comes off as a racial; socioeconomic trade off where the more privileged you are, the more likely youâ€™re going to have a criminal case swayed in your favor particularly in states like georgia, tennessee, texas and florida among others. both cases mentioned above deal with sexual assault; both have evidence of sex abuse: one l with the abuser walking free because he was privileged to obtain a plea deal and the other sentenced to spend the rest of her life in prison for escaping her rapist(s) by taking her abusers life. with all this talk of #metoo and #timesup it appears the courts are keeping up with their tradition of ignoring society and the media and drifting off into their own world where legality and common sense donâ€™t always add up...

"there is nothing more dangerous than silence. it only benefits the author of abuse." speak. to somebody, anybody. i feel broken looking around its so common so many people are in this position and dying with their secrets.

when you speak the power is broken, it releases you into a new freedom. and it takes back your power as the victim - that's what you are. you're on the other side of somebody else's shitty decisions.

reclaim your ground! enough has been taken from you.

text:
there's a powerful reason to call ourselves "survivors" over "victims." victimhood locks your mind in a state of powerlessness. and even worse, you believe you will never get past the pain and the trauma and the life-altering consequences that come with being a victim.
.
when you are sexually assaulted or wronged in any other way that causes damage to your personhood, your mind is thrown into this state. it's unfair. it's absolutely never deserved or justified. it's quite plainly a violation of your human rights. but, eventually, you have to stop calling yourself a victim and start calling yourself a survivor.
.
you have to be the person to initiate the climb out of the victim state of mind.
.
you have to be the person to decide you want to heal, and that healing is a long, difficult, and tumultuous process that never happens linearly.
.
and nobody else can tell you to make your mind transition from victim to survivor. you decide when you're ready to make that happen. but, it has to happen at some point for you to be able to find happiness and health in this one lifeâ€“ the only life that we know for sure.
.
changes to the institutions that neglect us cannot begin to make necessary changes until we rise above victim status and begin to call ourselves survivors instead. and we are survivors. to be able to resiliently rise above the pain and trauma, not just once but as many times as it resurfaces throughout our lifetimes â€“that's surviving.
.
when we realize we can survive our traumas is when we can begin to find our voices again. that's when we must start coming forward, boldly and unapologetically, to call out those responsible for the neglect of our human rights.
.
and if you haven't been able to find your voice, i will always be here to speak on behalf of survivors. please reach out if you ever need a listening ear or even a storyteller to help you feel heard.
-
#sexualassault #sexualassaultsurvivor #metoo #timesup #rapeculture #consentculture #survivor #makeyourvoiceheard #writer #humanrights #activist #humanist #lifestlye #influencer #entrepreneur

text:
the following is a true story of a survivor of human trafficking. this story includes sensitive language surrounding sexual assault. please consider this before reading further:â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
"ella* is an american girl who had been in the foster care system for years. it was family after family. home after home. her life was always changing. when she turned 18, she was too old to stay in the system. she felt hurt and alone with nowhere to go and no one to turn to. one day, a woman approached her asking if she needed any food or help. ella thought this woman really cared about her. the woman said her boyfriend was a good guy and could take care of her, and ella chose to trust her.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
while everything seemed okay at first, the boyfriend suddenly told ella that she owed him money for everything he had provided for her. he began trafficking her, forcing her to go from city to city...â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
but one day, ella met with a man who she thought was paying for a service. he turned out to be a law enforcement officer who offered to help. despite the risk, she trusted him and told him her story. the officer assisted her to safety, her trafficker was arrested, and she was connected with a21. the team at a21 was able to find her safe housing and provide the services she needed to start building the life she envisioned for herself."â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
we partner with a21 year after year to provide the funds to continue helping women like ella, in america and at their offices around the world. find out more at a21.org, and join us this dressember as we create more opportunities for girls like ella. â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
- photo and info credit from dressember.orgâ €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
